      "source": [
        "**To program Planck's law of radiation for a given temperature in Python, we can use the following code:**\n",
        "\n",
        "This code defines the planck function, which takes in a wavelength wav and temperature T and returns the spectral radiance of a blackbody at that wavelength and temperature. It then defines a wavelength range and a temperature, and calculates the spectral radiance using planck. Finally, it plots the spectral radiance as a function of wavelength."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "pJXMfm4TjnFF"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "# Constants\n",
        "h = 6.626e-34  # Planck's constant\n",
        "c = 3.0e+8  # Speed of light\n",
        "k = 1.38e-23  # Boltzmann constant\n",
        "\n",
        "def planck(wav, T):\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    Returns the spectral radiance of a blackbody at temperature T and wavelength wav.\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    a = 2.0*h*c**2\n",
        "    b = h*c/(wav*k*T)\n",
        "    intensity = a/ ( (wav**5)*(np.exp(b) - 1.0) )\n",
        "    return intensity\n",
        "\n",
        "# Define wavelength range\n",
        "wav = np.linspace(1e-9, 3e-6, 1000)  # meters\n",
        "\n",
        "# Define temperature\n",
        "T = 5800  # Kelvin\n",
        "\n",
        "# Calculate Planck's law\n",
        "intensity = planck(wav, T)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot Planck's law\n",
        "plt.plot(wav*1e9, intensity)\n",
        "plt.xlabel('Wavelength (nm)')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Spectral Radiance (W sr$^{-1}$ m$^{-3}$)')\n",
        "plt.title(\"Planck's Law of Radiation for T = {} K\".format(T))\n",
        "plt.show()\n"

        "**To show the short and long wavelengths limit, we can modify the code as follows:**\n",
        "\n",
        "This code adds two vertical lines to the plot, one at the short wavelength limit and one at the long wavelength limit. The short wavelength limit is given by h*c/(lambda*k*T), where lambda is the shortest wavelength in the range, and the long wavelength limit is given by h*c/(lambda*k*T), where lambda is the longest wavelength in the range."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "s79RTKMxjv6j"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Define wavelength range\n",
        "wav = np.linspace(1e-12, 1e-6, 1000)  # meters\n",
        "\n",
        "# Define temperature\n",
        "T = 5800  # Kelvin\n",
        "\n",
        "# Calculate Planck's law\n",
        "intensity = planck(wav, T)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot Planck's law\n",
        "plt.plot(wav*1e9, intensity)\n",
        "plt.xlabel('Wavelength (nm)')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Spectral Radiance (W sr$^{-1}$ m$^{-3}$)')\n",
        "plt.title(\"Planck's Law of Radiation for T = {} K\".format(T))\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot short wavelength limit\n",
        "plt.axvline(x=h*c/(wav[-1]*k*T)*1e9, color='r', linestyle='--', label='Short Wavelength Limit')\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot long wavelength limit\n",
        "plt.axvline(x=h*c/(wav[0]*k*T)*1e9, color='g', linestyle='--', label='Long Wavelength Limit')\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()\n"

        "# Define wavelength range\n",
        "wav = np.linspace(1e-12, 1e-6, 1000)  # meters\n",
        "\n",
        "# Define temperature\n",
        "T = 5800  # Kelvin\n",

        "plt.title(\"Planck's Law of Radiation for T = {} K\".format(T))\n",

        "\n",
        "# Plot long wavelength limit\n",
        "plt.axvline(x=h*c/(wav[0]*k*T)*1e9, color='g', linestyle='--', label='Long Wavelength Limit')\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot short wavelength limit\n",
        "plt.subplot(3, 1, 2)\n",
        "plt.plot(wav*1e9, intensity)\n",

        "plt.ylabel('Spectral Radiance (W sr$^{-1}$ m$^{-3}$)')\n",
        "plt.title(\"Short Wavelength Limit\")\n",
        "plt.xlim(0, 10)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot long wavelength limit\n",
        "plt.subplot(3, 1, 3)\n",

        "plt.xlabel('Wavelength (nm)')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Spectral Radiance (W sr$^{-1}$ m$^{-3}$)')\n",
        "plt.title(\"Long Wavelength Limit\")\n",
        "plt.xlim(1000, 3000)\n",
